alue="ecat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Economic News</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:e212"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gcat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Political/General News</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gpol"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvote"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvote1"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gpir"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Politics/International Relations</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gpol"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvote"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvote1"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Top of the News</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Mahathir: Next elections a do or die for Malaysia's future</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Ex-PM worries for his country if Najib stays in power and govt continues on debt path</Para><Para>Former premier Mahathir Mohamad sees his quest to unseat Prime Minister Najib Razak at the upcoming Malaysian elections as a do or die mission.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>If the incumbent leader is not defeated at elections expected within weeks, Datuk Seri Najib will become unbeatable, says his predecessor and now rival for the premiership, Tun Dr Mahathir.</Para><Para>"If he wins, he will be very strong. So this is our last opportunity to unseat him. If we lose this, there is no future. He will die (one day), but the legacy that he leaves behind will kill all the prime ministers who follow. They cannot solve this," he told The Sunday Times in an interview last week.</Para><Para>Dr Mahathir said it would be "disastrous" if Mr Najib remained in power as the government continues to go deeper into debt to cover its spending.</Para><Para>Dr Mahathir, who was in power for 22 years, was one of several Umno leaders who tried to force the party president to step down after revelations in 2015 that some US$700 million (S$921 million) linked to controversial state investor 1Malaysia Development Berhad (1MDB) had been found in the latter's personal accounts.</Para><Para>But Mr Najib insisted the money was a political donation from the Saudi royal family, and sacked his critics, including his deputy premier, from the government. The then Attorney-General - who has sole discretion over criminal prosecution - was also replaced, and sweeping changes to the anti-corruption agency ensued.</Para><Para>This has caused critics to accuse Mr Najib of abusing his position to halt investigations against him, and also of centralising executive power in his office to ensure that the ruling elite remains loyal to him.</Para><Para>PERILOUS PATH</Para><Para>He (PM Najib) wants to do big things but he has no money and he thought borrowing money is okay... He's borrowing RM55 billion, RM42 billion... This will destroy the economy, the strength of the country. You will become like Greece.</Para><Para>DR MAHATHIR MOHAMAD, referring to debt incurred by a planned East Coast Rail Link and 1MDB.</Para><Para>But Dr Mahathir himself stands accused of suppressing dissent during his time in charge, leading some rights activists to criticise the opposition for putting democratic reforms on the back burner by accepting the long-serving former premier as its leader.</Para><Para>But the 92-year-old says the debt incurred by the Najib administration is what will trouble him most should he return to power.</Para><Para>"Returning to democracy is easy. Going back to the rule of law is also easy. Limiting the terms of the prime minister would be easy. But the borrowing that Najib has indulged in is now about RM900 billion (S$302 billion). I don't know how to handle that," he said.</Para><Para>Government debt stood at more than RM687 billion as of last September, while it also guarantees nearly RM200 billion worth of debt raised by state firms.</Para><Para>"He (PM Najib) wants to do big things but he has no money and he thought borrowing money is okay. In my time, I never borrowed one billion but he's borrowing RM55 billion, RM42 billion..." Dr Mahathir said, referring to debt incurred by a planned East Coast Rail Link and 1MDB, respectively.</Para><Para>"This will destroy the economy, the strength of the country. You will become like Greece."</Para><Para>bn.jpg</Para><Para>Related Story</Para><Para>Malaysia's election: Get the latest updates here</Para><Para>Related Story</Para><Para>Mahathir's unfinished business</Para><Para>Mr Najib has repeatedly dismissed concerns about Malaysia's debt in the past, pointing to positive reports by credit rating agencies, and how other developed countries such as Singapore, the United Kingdom and Japan have higher debt-to-GDP levels compared with Malaysia's 51 per cent.</Para><Para>Instead, Mr Najib has accused Dr Mahathir's Pakatan Harapan opposition pact of making irresponsible promises in its election manifesto, which will incur another RM416 billion of debt, with abolishing highway tolls and the goods and services tax expected to cost RM383 billion.</Para><Para>Dr Mahathir, who stepped down as prime minister in 2003, admitted in the interview that "sometimes I felt that we may not be able to fulfil our promise".</Para><Para>"Our party, our coalition partners, you know they are very socialistic, they like to give things to people. I told them it cannot be done. You want to remove all the toll roads, they want to give free.</Para><Para>"I say, look, we have to maintain the roads. You have to build more roads. Where do you get the money if you're trying to maintain this road by yourself? But they want popularity, so they prefer to promise this thing," he added.</Para><Para>SEE INSIGHT</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Shannon TeohMalaysia Bureau Chief In Cyberjaya, Malaysia </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">Dr Mahathir Mohamad giving a speech after launching the four-party coalition Pact of Hope (Pakatan Harapan) election manifesto in Shah Alam, outside Kuala Lumpur. </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

